.TH "SIGCONVERT" "1" "13 May 2026" "" "The Regina Handbook"

.SH NAME
sigconvert \- Convert between generations of isomorphism signature or    knot/link signature
.SH SYNOPSIS

\fBsigconvert\fR [ \fB-k, --knot\fR | \fB-2, --dim2\fR | \fB-3, --dim3\fR | \fB-4, --dim4\fR | \fB-d, --dim=\fIdimension\fB\fR ] [ \fB-g, --gen=\fIgeneration\fB\fR ] [ \fB--\fR ] { \fB\fIsignature\fB\fR\fI ...\fR | \fB-\fR }


\fBsigconvert\fR { \fB-v, --version\fR | \fB-?, --help\fR }

.SH "DESCRIPTION"
.PP
Converts between first-generation and second-generation isomorphism
signatures for triangulations, or between first-generation and
second-generation knot/link signatures.
.PP
In Regina, triangulations and knot/link diagrams are often represented
using \fIisomorphism signatures\fR and
\fIknot/link signatures\fR respectively.
These signatures are short pieces of text that identify a triangulation
or link diagram uniquely up to combinatorial isomorphism (which for
triangulations includes relabellings of top-dimensional simplices and
their vertices, and for knot/link diagrams includes relabellings of
crossings as well as various rotation/reflection/reversal operations).
.PP
The format of these signatures changed in Regina\~8.0.
The old signatures, used in Regina\~<=\~7.x, are called
\fIfirst-generation\fR signatures.
The new signatures, introduced in Regina\~8.0, are called
\fIsecond-generation\fR signatures.
Second-generation signatures are smaller, often faster to compute, and are
recommended for use in new projects.
Nowadays you should only use first-generation signatures if you need to
maintain compatibility with older versions of Regina.
.PP
The purpose of \fBsigconvert\fR is simply to convert
between these two formats.  It will take a list of signatures as
input, convert them to the requested format (second-generation by default,
or first-generation if you pass \fB--gen=1\fR), and write the
converted signatures to standard output, each on a separate line.
.PP
The input signatures are assumed to represent 3-dimensional triangulations
unless one of the other link or dimension options is passed
(\fB--knot\fR, \fB--dim2\fR,
\fB--dim4\fR, or \fB--dim=...\fR).
Your input may include first-generation signatures, second-generation
signatures, or a mix of both.
.PP
There are two ways to provide the input signatures.
The simplest way is to pass them as command-line arguments.
Alternatively (for example, if you have a large number of signatures to
convert), you can pass a dash (\fB-\fR)
on the command-line instead, which will instruct
\fBsigconvert\fR to read the
input signatures from standard input (one per line).
Both methods are illustrated in the examples below.
.sp
.RS
.B "Tip:"
Very large triangulations or links have signatures that begin with a dash
(-).  Such signatures could be mistaken for options
when passing them on the command line.  To avoid this, you can pass the
special option \fB--\fR immediately before the signatures:
this indicates that all command-line options have finished,
and whatever comes next should be treated as input signatures.

.nf
    example$ \fBsigconvert -- -b-LLvALwvM...\fR
.fi
.RE
.SH "OPTIONS"
.TP
\fB-k, --knot\fR
Indicates that the input signatures represent knots or links.
.TP
\fB-2, --dim2\fR
Indicates that the input signatures represent 2-dimensional
triangulations.
.TP
\fB-3, --dim3 (default)\fR
Indicates that the input signatures represent 3-dimensional
triangulations.

This is the default if none of the arguments
\fB--knot\fR,
\fB--dim2\fR, \fB--dim3\fR,
\fB--dim4\fR,
or \fB--dim=...\fR are passed.
.TP
\fB-4, --dim4\fR
Indicates that the input signatures represent 4-dimensional
triangulations.
.TP
\fB-d, --dim=\fIdimension\fB\fR
Indicates that the input signatures represent triangulations of the
given dimension.  Here you can pass any dimension supported by
Regina (including higher dimensions >=\~5).

If none of the arguments \fB--knot\fR,
\fB--dim2\fR, \fB--dim3\fR,
\fB--dim4\fR or \fB--dim=...\fR
are passed, then the default is to assume triangulations of
dimension\~3.
.TP
\fB-g, --gen=\fIgeneration\fB\fR
Indicates whether to output first-generation signatures or
second-generation signatures.

The default is to output second-generation signatures.
.TP
\fB--\fR
Indicates that all other options have finished, and whatever comes
next on the command line should be treated as the input signatures.

This is useful when you have a signature that begins with a dash,
to avoid confusing your input signature with a regular command line
option.
.TP
\fB-v, --version\fR
Show which version of Regina is being used, and exit
immediately.
.TP
\fB-?, --help\fR
Display brief usage information, and exit immediately.
.SH "EXAMPLES"
.PP
The following example converts back and forth between 3-dimensional
isomorphism signature formats for the figure eight knot complement.
Here the first-generation signature is
cPcbbbiht, and the second-generation
signature is cV6cqb:

.nf
    example$ \fBsigconvert cPcbbbiht\fR
    cV6cqb
    example$ \fBsigconvert -g1 cV6cqb\fR
    cPcbbbiht
    example$
.fi
.PP
The next example converts knot/link signatures from first-generation
to second-generation, for both the Whitehead link and the Borromean rings:

.nf
    example$ \fBsigconvert -k fabcadefbcedvfpd gabcdgaecfgbfdeLwto\fR
    f3q7Gko
    gVc1JwUJ
    example$
.fi
.PP
Suppose you have a file \fIsigs.txt\fR containing
first-generation 3-dimensional isomorphism signatures (one per line).
For instance, you might have obtained this from running
tricensus --sigs using an older version of Regina.
To convert these into second-generation signatures, you can instruct
\fBsigconvert\fR to use standard input:

.nf
    example$ \fBcat sigs.txt\fR
    eLAkbcbddhhwhr
    eLAkbcbddhhwqj
    eLAkbcbddhxwqs
    \&...
    example$ \fBcat sigs.txt | sigconvert -\fR
    epAA3aaGi
    ehrBRr4cl
    ehrBRrici
    \&...
    example$
.fi
.SH "MACOS USERS"
.PP
If you downloaded a drag-and-drop app bundle, this utility is
shipped inside it.  If you dragged Regina to the main
Applications folder, you can run it as
/Applications/Regina.app/Contents/MacOS/sigconvert\&.
.SH "WINDOWS USERS"
.PP
The command-line utilities are installed beneath the
\fIProgram\~Files\fR directory; on some
machines this directory is called
\fIProgram\~Files\~(x86)\fR\&.
You can start this utility by running
c:\\Program\~Files\\Regina\\Regina\~8.0\\bin\\sigconvert.exe\&.
